Analysis of Voter Trends in the United States of America¶

Rohan Dewan, Fall 2024 CMSC 320 Project¶

Introduction¶

As a Computer Science and Political Science dual degree, I'm often posed with the question what are the largest intersections between my fields of study? Following the 2024 United States General Election, Political Science has never been more scrutinized. Many pundits, scholars, and voters alike have wondered how decisions were so incorrectly made, predictions fell so far from the truth, and campaign strategies had such unexpected results. Nuanced social science analysis is the backbone of political understanding, however, the randomness of election results shows that quantitative, scientific understanding is needed more than ever.

I wanted to do a political investigation for this datascience project. I intend to use election data over the last 50 or so years in presidential, sentate, and house elections to determine what political practices are best, how we can follow and predict trends, and what different campaigns/parties can do to shore up support moving forward. Some questions that I wish to answer (among others) include:

  • How do midterm elections predict presidential elections in the next cycle (and vice versa)?
  • How to different population sizes vote and what can political campaigns do to attract these demographics in the future?
  • Do any political parties show dominance over the others and if so, how has it evolved?

Throughout this tutorial, I will properly clean my data, make preliminary observations, feature engineer, and apply machine learning methods to create recommendation and prediction models. Paired with my data visualizations, I'll use all my findings to make policy suggestions that political groups and parties can use in future elections. In this new era of political uncertainty, these findings will prove vital.

Data Curation¶

I've sourced all my data frome https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataverse/harvard which uses data from MIT's election data and science lab. It has detailed information about senate, congressional, and presidential elections that span from 1976 to 2022 (only 2020 when it comes to presidential elections). I downloaded these three datasets and uploaded it to my google drive. From there, I imported these csv files as Dataframes using pandas's read_csv function.

# Extracting information from census.gov
url = "https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/dec/popchange-data-text.html"
response = requests.get(url)
if response.status_code == 200:
    print("Successfully fetched the webpage")
else:
    print(f"Failed to fetch the webpage: {response.status_code}")
    exit()

# Parse the HTML content
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
tables = soup.find_all('table')

dataframes = []
for i, table in enumerate(tables):
    # Use StringIO to handle HTML as a file-like object
    table_html = str(table)
    population_df = pd.read_html(StringIO(table_html))[0]
    dataframes.append(population_df)
    print(f"Processed table {i + 1}")

# Storing CSV to avoid going through the entire webscraping process again later is a good idea for maintenance and efficiency if ever required
for i, df in enumerate(dataframes):
    df.to_csv(f"table_{i + 1}.csv", index=False)

Cleaning Data¶

Often in data science projects, the standard procedure is to convert date and time into NumPy's datetime format for more functionality and standardization. However, since we are only dealing with election years and not more specific date or time information, we can leave this field/feature in int64 for all of our dataframes. Everything else will be stored in string form.

In [7]:
# Make a copy of the DataFrame to avoid modifying a slice
president_df = president_df.copy()

# Make sure the values are the correct data types
for col in president_df.columns:
    if president_df[col].dtype == 'object':
        president_df[col] = president_df[col].astype('str')
president_df['writein'] = president_df['writein'].map({'True': True, 'False': False})

# Filter out writein rows and other irrelevant columns that woud complicate our analysis
president_df = president_df[president_df['writein'] == False]
president_df = president_df.drop(columns=['writein', 'party_detailed', 'version', 'notes', 'state_fips', 'state_cen', 'state_ic'])

president_df = president_df.groupby(['year', 'state'], group_keys=False).apply(lambda x: x.nlargest(3, 'candidatevotes'))
president_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
president_df.rename(columns={'party_simplified': 'party'}, inplace=True)

# Reduce analysis to three party categories
president_df['party'] = np.where(president_df['party'].isin(['DEMOCRAT', 'REPUBLICAN']), president_df['party'], 'OTHER')

Exploratory Data Analysis and Data Visualization¶

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is a vital step for any datascience project. It allows us to understand the data better and will provide key insights into voter behavior and election dynamics across our datasets. We can identify preliminary patterns, understand distributions, and explore relationships. For more information about EDA, go here: https://www.ibm.com/topics/exploratory-data-analysis.

I'd like to see if house congressional races during the midterms are an accurate predictor for how a state will vote for the next presidential election. We can average the results of each state's house elections during the midterm to get the majority party and then see how often this party matches the winning party per vote during the subsequent presidential election.

In [11]:
# Create a list of just the midterm elections so we can easily narrow down dataframe
midterm_years = [1978, 1982, 1986, 1990, 1994, 1998, 2002, 2006, 2010, 2014, 2018]
midterm_df = house_df[house_df['year'].isin(midterm_years)]

# I combine the votes for each election by state and party to give us a rough idea of which party "won support dominantly"
midterm_results = midterm_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party'])['candidatevotes'].sum().reset_index()
max_votes = midterm_results.groupby(['year', 'state'])['candidatevotes'].transform('max')
midterm_results = midterm_results[midterm_results['candidatevotes'] == max_votes]
midterm_results.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
midterm_results

# Do the same thing with the presidential election years with the president df
presidential_results = president_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party'])['candidatevotes'].sum().reset_index()
max_votes = presidential_results.groupby(['year', 'state'])['candidatevotes'].transform('max')
presidential_results = presidential_results[presidential_results['candidatevotes'] == max_votes]

midterm_results['year'] = midterm_results['year'].astype(int) + 2

merged_df = pd.merge(midterm_results, presidential_results, on=['year', 'state'], how='inner', suffixes=('_midterm', '_presidential'))
merged_df

# Function to calculate the vote margin
def calculate_margin(df):
    df = df.sort_values(by='candidatevotes', ascending=False)
    top_votes = df.iloc[0]['candidatevotes']
    second_votes = df.iloc[1]['candidatevotes'] if len(df) > 1 else 0
    return top_votes - second_votes

# Calculate margins for each election type (president, house, senate)
president_margin = president_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party']).apply(calculate_margin).reset_index(name='Vote Margin')
house_margin = house_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party']).apply(calculate_margin).reset_index(name='Vote Margin')
senate_margin = senate_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party']).apply(calculate_margin).reset_index(name='Vote Margin')

# Add election type column
president_margin['Election_Type'] = 'Presidential'
house_margin['Election_Type'] = 'House'
senate_margin['Election_Type'] = 'Senate'

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

Importance of Machine Learning for this project

Machine learning is a broad field of comptuer science and encompasses many algorithms and techniques where we wish to learn from data and use our findings to make predictions on larger sets of data/observations from the world. Machine learning often involves training models on sets of data which will then allow the model to accurately predict things based on unseen data. Machine Learning includes supervised learning (using labeled data), unsupervised learning (using unlabeled data, relying on natural clustering), reinforcement learning, and more.

You may wonder what can be done with political data beyond our normal statistical tests that are ubiquitious in most political science research and literature. However, our models can help teach us things about politics that simple quantitative and qualitative analysis would not yield. I posed several open ended questions in the introductio of this project, however, we are not looking for a hyperspecific model. There are many dimensions and attributes of elections and election cycles that we can investigate, so I will approach just a few of the many possibilities.

First, I'll use a Graident Boosting Regressor to incrementally find a regression model that accurately predicts election turnout. Though this is not a partisan metric, it's important to understand how turnout rates change when it comes to our shifting population. Following this, I'll answer one of the large questions I posed in the introduction where I try to determine if midterm election results can help use predict the following presidential election. This will be done with a Random Forest Classifier model. Both of these models are from the sklearn python library. You can read more about the library and its many modeling applications here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/index.html.

Voter Turnout Regression Model

For our turnout model, we first must manipulate our population data more. Because we are looking at nationwide trends, I am just going to collapse our population_df into a dictionary based on census years. This can then be applied to our president_df, house_df, and senate_df to check turnout in each election. Because we don't want to double count votes, I'm going to divide the total vote amount by the number of national elections in that cycle (three for the presidential years, two for the midterm years). I know that this method is slightly flawed, but for the scope of the project it will have to do.

In [21]:
nationwide_population = population_df.sum().to_dict()

print(nationwide_population)

# Aggregate votes from president_df, house_df, and senate_df
president_votes = president_df.groupby('year')['candidatevotes'].sum().reset_index(name='Presidential_Votes')
house_votes = house_df.groupby('year')['candidatevotes'].sum().reset_index(name='House_Votes')

# Merge the vote data
vote_totals = pd.merge(president_votes, house_votes, on='year', how='outer')
vote_totals = pd.merge(vote_totals, senate_votes, on='year', how='outer')

# Calculate total votes per year
vote_totals['total_votes'] = vote_totals[['Presidential_Votes', 'House_Votes', 'Senate_Votes']].sum(axis=1, skipna=True)

# Merge vote_totals with population information to extract turnout
turnout_df = vote_totals.copy()

turnout_df['decade'] = (turnout_df['year'] - (turnout_df['year'] % 10)).astype(int)
turnout_df['turnout_rate'] = turnout_df['total_votes'] / turnout_df['decade'].map(lambda x: nationwide_population[str(x)])
turnout_df['population'] = turnout_df['decade'].map(lambda x: nationwide_population[str(x)])

# Divide turnout by 3 in presidential election years and by 2 in midterms to get average turnout for national elections
turnout_df.loc[turnout_df['year'] % 4 == 0, 'turnout_rate'] /= 3
turnout_df.loc[(turnout_df['year'] % 4 == 2), 'turnout_rate'] /= 2

turnout_df = turnout_df.drop(index=23)
turnout_df = turnout_df.drop(index=24)

Following this, we will do some feature engineering for our population amount and turnout rate. Because the census only occurs once every 10 years but we have elections 5 times for each census cycle, we need to l,og transform our data so that we can simulate continuous growth even during non-census years. This will help our model have a better fit for unseen data. After this, I'll use a GradientBoostingRegressor model from scikit to create a linear regression that models turnout rate based on population. To learn more about what the regressor does under the hood, you can look at its documentation here: https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.GradientBoostingRegressor.html.

In [22]:
# Feature Engineering: Add log-transformed and percentage change columns because we only have census updates every 10 years so need another way to simulate growth
turnout_df['log_population'] = np.log(turnout_df['population'])
turnout_df['log_total_votes'] = np.log(turnout_df['total_votes'])
turnout_df['population_vote_ratio'] = (
    turnout_df['total_votes'] / turnout_df['population']
)

# Prepare features and target
features = turnout_df[['year', 'log_population', 'log_total_votes', 'population_vote_ratio']]
target = turnout_df['turnout_rate']

# Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Gradient Boosting Regressor Model Training
model = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=42, n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='r2')
print(f"Cross-Validation R²: {cv_scores.mean():.2f} ± {cv_scores.std():.2f}")

# Predictions
y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluation
rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train))
rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test))
r2_train = r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
r2_test = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

print(f"Train RMSE: {rmse_train:.2f}, Test RMSE: {rmse_test:.2f}")
print(f"Train R²: {r2_train:.2f}, Test R²: {r2_test:.2f}")

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

Presidential Election Prediction

Our next machine learning method will be to create a model that can predict presidential election results based on the preceding midterm elections. Political scholars often try to use these paired election years to collect information and make predictions, however, quantitative analysis may be more robust. We will first aggregate house and senate election results during the midterms and then use a RandomForestClassifier to try and extract patterns in the data that we can reproduce in future real-world scenarios. To learn more about the principle of Random Forest Classifiers, go to this website: https://builtin.com/data-science/random-forest-algorithm#:~:text=Random%20forest%20is%20a%20predictive,other%20approaches%20would%20be%20better. We are not describing the data in this case but predicting.

In [23]:
# Aggregate House and Senate midterm election results
midterm_years = [year for year in range(1974, 2021, 4)]  # List of midterm election years
midterm_house = house_df[house_df['year'].isin(midterm_years)]
midterm_senate = senate_df[senate_df['year'].isin(midterm_years)]

# Combine House and Senate votes by year, state, and party
midterm_results = (
    pd.concat([midterm_house, midterm_senate])
    .groupby(['year', 'state', 'party'])['candidatevotes']
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
)

# Aggregate total votes and calculate vote shares for each party
midterm_pivot = midterm_results.pivot(index=['year', 'state'], columns='party', values='candidatevotes').fillna(0)
midterm_pivot['total_votes'] = midterm_pivot.sum(axis=1)
for party in midterm_results['party'].unique():
    midterm_pivot[f'{party}_share'] = midterm_pivot[party] / midterm_pivot['total_votes']

# Aggregate Presidential election results
presidential_results = (
    president_df.groupby(['year', 'state', 'party'])['candidatevotes']
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
)

# Identify the winning party in each state for the Presidential election
presidential_results['is_winning_party'] = (
    presidential_results.groupby(['year', 'state'])['candidatevotes'].transform('max') == presidential_results['candidatevotes']
)
presidential_results = presidential_results[presidential_results['is_winning_party']].drop(columns=['is_winning_party'])
presidential_results = presidential_results[['year', 'state', 'party']].rename(columns={'party': 'winning_party'})

# Align Presidential elections with the previous midterm elections (2 year gap between them)
presidential_results['midterm_year'] = presidential_results['year'] - 2
data = pd.merge(
    presidential_results,
    midterm_pivot.reset_index(),
    left_on=['midterm_year', 'state'],
    right_on=['year', 'state'],
    how='inner'
)

data = data.drop(columns=['year_x', 'midterm_year', 'year_y'])
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
data['winning_party_encoded'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['winning_party'])
features = data.drop(columns=['state', 'winning_party', 'winning_party_encoded'])
target = data['winning_party_encoded']

# Train/Test Split, Training Random Forest Classifier
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, n_estimators=100)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions and Evaluation
y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)

print("Train Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train))

Presidential/Congressional Coinfluence?

I'm also curious about how presidential candidate performance relates to house congressional performance in the same election year. As a candidate receives a greater share of the presidential vote in each state, how many house races does that candidate's party also win? To do this we will use the GradientBoostRegressor machine learning technique again. We first have to update our dataframes so we can easily extract the number of house races won per party per state per presidential election year and cross analyze this with presidential vote shares.

In [24]:
# Filter for presidential election years
presidential_years = president_df['year'].unique()
presidential_years = [year for year in presidential_years if year % 4 == 0]

# Aggregate presidential election performance at the state level
state_presidential = (
    president_df[president_df['year'].isin(presidential_years)]
    .groupby(['state', 'year', 'party'])['candidatevotes']
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
)

# Calculate vote shares for Democrats and Republicans
state_presidential = state_presidential.pivot(
    index=['state', 'year'], columns='party', values='candidatevotes'
).fillna(0)
state_presidential['total_votes'] = state_presidential.sum(axis=1)
state_presidential['dem_share'] = state_presidential['DEMOCRAT'] / state_presidential['total_votes']
state_presidential['rep_share'] = state_presidential['REPUBLICAN'] / state_presidential['total_votes']
state_presidential.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Filter data for presidential election years
house_presidential_years = house_df[house_df['year'].isin(presidential_years)]

# Determine the winning party for each district
house_presidential_years['is_winning_party'] = (
    house_presidential_years.groupby(['year', 'state', 'district'])['candidatevotes']
    .transform('max') == house_presidential_years['candidatevotes']
)

# Filter only rows where the party won
winning_house = house_presidential_years[house_presidential_years['is_winning_party']]

# Count wins for each party by state and year
state_congressional = (
    winning_house.groupby(['state', 'year', 'party'])
    .size()
    .unstack(fill_value=0)
    .reset_index()
    .rename(columns={'DEMOCRAT': 'dem_wins', 'REPUBLICAN': 'rep_wins'})
)

state_congressional.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Merge presidential performance and congressional wins
data = pd.merge(state_presidential, state_congressional, on=['state', 'year'], how='inner')

Now that we have properly prepared and transformed our data, we will train and test our models for the two major parties.

In [25]:
# Features and targets
features = data[['dem_share', 'rep_share']]

The way that I would explain the diminishing returns and later decrease in the average congressional seats won per party as their presidential vote share increases is that very small states start to skew the numbers. In [29]:
# Polynomial Regression Function
def plot_polynomial_regression(x, y, degree, color, label):
    # Fit polynomial regression
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    poly = Polynomial(coeffs[::-1])  # Reverse coefficients for Polynomial
    x_range = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), 500)
    y_pred = poly(x_range)

    # Plot regression line
    plt.plot(x_range, y_pred, color=color, label=f'{label} (Degree {degree})')

# Create the scatterplot with polynomial regression for both parties
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Scatter and polynomial regression for Democrats
sns.scatterplot(x='dem_share', y='dem_wins', data=data, color='blue', alpha=0.6, label='Democratic Wins')
plot_polynomial_regression(data['dem_share'], data['dem_wins'], degree=3, color='blue', label='Democratic Trend')

# Scatter and polynomial regression for Republicans
sns.scatterplot(x='rep_share', y='rep_wins', data=data, color='red', alpha=0.6, label='Republican Wins')
plot_polynomial_regression(data['rep_share'], data['rep_wins'], degree=3, color='red', label='Republican Trend')

# Chart customization
plt.title('Response of Congressional Seats to Presidential Vote Share (Polynomial Regression)', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Presidential Vote Share (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Congressional Seats Won', fontsize=12)
plt.legend(title='Party')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Before trying the degree three polynomial regression, I tried a degree two. I omitted that part because I think three works better fo this data (indicating how eventually the average number of seats won will decrease in those smaller partisan states). This is an example of how fitting and choosing your model is not always based on numbers but some situational and field-based understanding. The reason our models don't go higher to the points above is they are further from the denser center (though not necessarily outliers). Thus, we can conclude the relationship between presidential vote share and congressional seats one is more of a cubic shape across the past half century of election data.

Conclusions and Policy Suggestions¶

From EDA

Overall, we've learned much about election dynamics and voting patterns from both our exploratory data anlaysis and machine learning/visualization. From EDA, we established that beyond anything else, politics is fickle. Whether it comes to midterm and presidential election years, nationwide party performance in a single year, and more, we can't always determine if there are statistical relationships. However, we do see that Democrats traditionally have experienced more extreme maxima relative to the Republicans and have overall higher vote sums on average. However, this popularity does not always translate into electoral victories because of overrepresentation in both the sentate, congress, and electoral college for smaller Republican states. What this tells me most is that we must focus on election victories for substantial policy recommendations. Another interesting thing to note from EDA was that Republicans are gaining on (or have suprassed) Democrats when it comes to total house election votes. This is not mirrored in the senate. A question that we can pose to political scientists or strategists is why is this happening? They must focus on the smallest districts and see why GOP members have attracted more voters than in the best. Are the Democrats proving to be a more federal/statewide party and neglecting the interests of their local constituencies?

From ML

When it comes to our Machine Learning section, we gleaned several insights that can help politicians and campaigns over the next few elections.

Voter Turnout

  • As we observed, our model very accurately predicts voter turnout with a nearly perfect fitting line on both test and validation groups. The model's accurate predictions can help identify states with historically low turnout rates. My suggestion to both parties is to deploy targeted voter outreach and education campaigns in states that can be identified with the model. It would be best to focus on high population-to-vote ratio gaps which is a key indicator of underpresentation. Additionally, parties should use the model to target states that are predicted to have higher turnout. Oftentimes, it's easier to convert already engaged voters than create a sense of voter efficacy in nonvoting populations.

Midterm/Presidential Cycle Prediction

  • Although I stated that the model used to predict presidential elections based on midterm results did not perform well, this does not mean we can't learn anything from that investigation. What this further proves to us is that midterm and presidential election behavior is wildly random. There is no use in predicting or allocating resources based on how a party performed before but to focus on contemporary trends that currently afflict voters. The biggest mistake that Democrats have made in the past 16 years, for example, is to assume that their coalitions will remain strong. The work and success they've had in previous elections (most notbaly under the Obama administration) have not carried over since. Our data demonstrates to both parties not to fall for this fatal miscalculation.

Presidential vs. Congressional Partisan Performance

  • This is the ML method that I found most interesting during this project. Political scientists and journalists always like to talk about the carryover effect that top of ticket candidates can have down the ballot. In 2024, this effect was seemingly more nebulous as gubernatorial, house, and senate races all broke with how voters made their presidential choice. Our initial plots and regressions show something incredibly interesting: house performance in states on average increase for a party as that party's presidnetial candidate receives a larger share of the vote. However, this eventually tapers of and begins to decrease with very high levels of presidential vote share (most likely due to partisanship in small, less populated states as I previously mentioned). Our regression also shows a cubic fit, with a similar peak and eventual decrease in average house seats won when presidential vote share goes up. I suggest that the Democrats invest in both presidential and house campaign advertisements in competitive districts because their top-of-ticket effect is even stronger than Republicans. Republicans should also make this investment, but probably won't benefit as much as Democratic candidates will. Additionally, this cubic fit shows that parties should avoid trying to win enclave districts (one or two districts that vote for one party in a state that as a whole goes mostly for the opposite party) because even as the presidential share goes up these districts remain brittle. Instead, attention show go to battleground states and states where a candidate has 10 to 20 percentage points more than their opponent (for whichever party is in the lead).

Overall

  • Political Science and politics are extremely hard to predict even with the most advanced models. That being said, advanced machine learning models can sometimes cut through supposition and show clear voter/election trends that can help parties restructure and optimize. The 2024 election defied many expectations on both sides of the aisle and proves the need for more data analysis in the field of politics.
